5. The function `fun i j ↦ if i ≤ j then ω ⟨i, j⟩ else ω ⟨j, i⟩` is therefore a function from `Fin n × Fin n` to `ℝ`.
6. `Matrix.of` takes such a function and creates a matrix. The resulting matrix is measurable if the underlying function is measurable.
7. The function `fun i j ↦ if i ≤ j then ω ⟨i, j⟩ else ω ⟨j, i⟩` is measurable because it is a pointwise operation on the indices `i` and `j`, and `ω` is a function from a measurable space (`Index n`, which is a `Finset` of pairs, hence countable, with the discrete σ-algebra) to `ℝ`.
