So, `wignerMatrixMap n` is `fun (ω : WignerSpace n) ↦ Matrix.of (wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω)`.

To show this is measurable, we need to show that for any set `s` in the codomain `Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ`, its preimage under `wignerMatrixMap n` is a measurable set in the domain `WignerSpace n`.
Let `f = wignerMatrixMap n`. Let `s` be a set in `Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ`. We need to show that `f⁻¹(s)` is measurable in `WignerSpace n`.
`f ω = Matrix.of (wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω)`.
So `f ω ∈ s` means `Matrix.of (wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω) ∈ s`.
This is equivalent to `(wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω) ∈ Matrix.of⁻¹(s)`.
The set `Matrix.of⁻¹(s)` is a subset of the space of functions `(Fin n → Fin n → ℝ)`.
We need to show that this set is measurable in `WignerSpace n`.
The function `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of (wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω)` is a composition of `Matrix.of` with the function `fun ω ↦ wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω`.
`Matrix.of` is continuous.
`fun ω ↦ wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω` is a product of functions `fun ω ↦ wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω i j` for all pairs `(i,j)`.
Each `fun ω ↦ wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω i j` is a composition of `ω` (which is `Index n → ℝ`) with an indexing operation.
