    <;> aesop
```

Now we need to prove that `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of (fun (p : {p : Fin n × Fin n // p.1 ≤ p.2}) ↦ (ω p.val))` is measurable.

The function `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of (fun (p : {p : Fin n × Fin n // p.1 ≤ p.2}) ↦ (ω p.val))` is a function from `WignerSpace n` to `Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ`. Let's denote `f_ω = fun (p : {p : Fin n × Fin n // p.1 ≤ p.2}) ↦ (ω p.val)`. Then the function is `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of (f_ω)`.

We need to show that `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of (f_ω)` is measurable. This is true if `fun ω ↦ f_ω` is measurable, and `Matrix.of` preserves measurability.

`f_ω` is `fun p ↦ ω p.val`. This is just `ω` itself, because `p.val` is the pair `(i, j)` such that `p` is `⟨(i, j), h⟩`. So `fun p ↦ ω p.val` is `fun p ↦ ω (⟨p.val.1, p.val.2⟩)`, which is just `ω`.

So, `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of (fun p ↦ ω p.val)` is `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of ω`.

To prove `Measurable (fun ω ↦ Matrix.of ω)`, we can use the fact that `fun ω ↦ Matrix.of ω` is a continuous function from `WignerSpace n` (which is compact) to `Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ` (which is also compact). A continuous function between compact spaces is measurable.

